Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C and remove the @21 Day Aged British Sirloin Steaks{2} from the fridge to allow it to come up to room temperature. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel). Pop the potatoes on a large, low-sided, wide #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, then season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer. Once your oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary, you want the potatoes nicely spread out.

Meanwhile, halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips then halve the slices. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}. Trim and thinly slice the @spring onion{1}. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}. Drain the @sweetcorn{150%g} in a #sieve{}.

Heat a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil). Once the pan is hot, add the sweetcorn and cook until nicely charred, ~{5-6%minutes}. Stir only twice during this time - you want the sweetcorn to pick up some nice colour. When done, add a splash of oil to the now-empty pan and lower the heat to medium. Add the pepper and shallot and fry until softened, ~{5-6%minutes}. Add the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Return the sweetcorn to the pan, stir together and remove from the heat.

Five mins before the potatoes are cooked, heat a drizzle of oil in a frying pan on high heat. Season the steaks with salt and pepper. When the oil is hot, lay the steaks in the pan and brown for ~{1%minute} on each side. Lower the heat slightly and cook for another ~{1-2%minutes} on each side for medium-rare.

> TIP: Cook for 1-2 mins more if you like it more cooked.
> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. The steak is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Once cooked, transfer to a #board{}, cover with #foil{} and allow to rest for a couple of mins.

Pop the frying pan back on medium heat (no need to wash). Add the @water{100%ml}, @chicken stock paste{10%g} and half the @chipotle paste{10%g}. Stir, bring to the boil and simmer until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add the @soured cream{75%g}, bring to the boil and then remove from the heat. Taste and add more chipotle paste if you like it hot.

> TIP: Add less chipotle paste if you don't like too much heat.

Reheat the sweetcorn mixture over medium heat. When the potato is crispy, add to the pan and stir through. Season with salt and pepper to taste. This is your hash. Slice the steak into 2cm strips. Reheat your sauce over medium heat.

Share the hash between your plates, top with the steak then drizzle over the creamy chipotle sauce. Finish with a sprinkling of coriander and the sliced spring onion. Enjoy!